import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Create a time array from 0 to 10 seconds with a sample rate of 100 Hz
time = np.linspace(0, 10, 1000)

# Define the frequencies and amplitudes of the waves
frequencies = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
amplitudes = [1, 0.5, 0.25, 0.1, 0.05]

# Create a figure with a size of 10x8 inches
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 8))

# Create a background gradient
for i in range(100):
    ax.plot(time, np.sin(time + i / 100), color=plt.cm.viridis(i / 100), alpha=0.1)

# Plot the sine and cosine waves
for i, (frequency, amplitude) in enumerate(zip(frequencies, amplitudes)):
    ax.plot(time, amplitude * np.sin(2 * np.pi * frequency * time), label=f'f={frequency}', color=plt.cm.tab20(i))
    ax.plot(time, amplitude * np.cos(2 * np.pi * frequency * time), label=f'f={frequency}', color=plt.cm.tab20(i))

# Add title and labels
ax.set_title('Harmonic Wave Composition')
ax.set_xlabel('Time (s)')
ax.set_ylabel('Amplitude')
ax.legend()

# Show the plot
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Create a figure with a size of 8x6 inches
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))

# Define the time array from 0 to 4 seconds with a step of 0.01 seconds
t = np.arange(0, 4, 0.01)

# Define the amplitude and frequency of the waves
amplitude = 1
frequency = 1

# Create a series of sine waves with different phase shifts
for i in range(5):
    # Calculate the phase shift for this wave
    phase_shift = i * np.pi / 2
    
    # Calculate the sine wave with the current phase shift
    wave = amplitude * np.sin(2 * np.pi * frequency * t + phase_shift)
    
    # Plot the wave
    ax.plot(t, wave, label=f'Phase Shift: {phase_shift:.2f} rad')

# Set the title and labels
ax.set_title('Phase-Shifted Sine Waves')
ax.set_xlabel('Time (s)')
ax.set_ylabel('Amplitude')
ax.legend()

# Show the plot
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Create an array of x values from 0 to 4π
x = np.linspace(0, 4 * np.pi, 1000)

# Create a figure with two subplots
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(8, 6))

# Plot the first cosine wave
axs[0].plot(x, np.cos(x), color='blue', label='Cosine wave')
axs[0].set_title('Cosine Wave')
axs[0].set_xlabel('x')
axs[0].set_ylabel('y')
axs[0].grid(True)

# Plot the second cosine wave shifted 180 degrees (π) relative to the first one
axs[1].plot(x, -np.cos(x), color='red', label='Shifted Cosine wave')
axs[1].set_title('Shifted Cosine Wave')
axs[1].set_xlabel('x')
axs[1].set_ylabel('y')
axs[1].grid(True)

# Add a legend to the second subplot
axs[1].legend()

# Layout so plots do not overlap
fig.tight_layout()

# Show the plot
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Define the number of points for the plot
n = 1000

# Generate the x values
x = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, n)

# Generate the sine and cosine waves
y_sin = np.sin(x)
y_cos = np.cos(x)

# Create a new figure
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

# Plot the sine and cosine waves
plt.plot(x, y_sin, label='Sine Wave', color='red')
plt.plot(x, y_cos, label='Cosine Wave', color='blue')

# Add a legend
plt.legend()

# Add title and labels
plt.title('Sine and Cosine Wave Interference')
plt.xlabel('Phase (radians)')
plt.ylabel('Amplitude')

# Show the plot
plt.show()
